# Helper function used to plot the confusion matricies of the CNN's in this assignment. 
def summarize_net(net, X_test, y_test, title_text = ''):
    plt.figure(figsize = (15,10))
    yhat = np.argmax(net.predict(X_test), axis = 1)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, yhat, average = 'micro')
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat)
    cm = cm/np.sum(cm, axis = 1)[:, np.newaxis]
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', cmap = 'Blues')
    plt.title(f'{title_text} : F1 Score {f1}')
    plt.show()

1. Dataset¶

In this lab I will use convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to perform object classification on a subset of the CIFAR-100 dataset. The CIFAR-100 dataset consists of tiny 32x32 pixel thumbnail images collected by Alex Krizhevsy, Vinod Nair, and Geoffrey Hinton for a paper entitled 'Learning Multiple Layers of Features from Tiny Images' by Alex Krizhevsky, 2009[2]. The table below shows the superclasses and classes of the images in the dataset.

2. Business Case¶

Autonomous cars are unmanned vehicles capable of driving without human interaction. In order to enable them to do this, autonomous cars must excellent at detecting and making sense of their surroundings. To do this, a variety of techniques such as radar, laser light, GPS, odometry, and computer vision are all utilized.

In this lab I will develop an object classification model, using convolutional nerual networks, that can be deployed in autonoumous driving vehicles to enhance their abillity to detect and interpret their surroundings. The prediction task of this object classification model is to classify objects autonomous driving vehicles are likely to encouter while driving. Therefore, I will only use a subset of the classes in the CIFAR-100 dataset representative of objects cars are likely to encounter while the road. From the dataset's superclass and class description above, I will use the classes 'people', 'trees', 'large man-made outdoor things', and 'vehicles 1', as the classes of objects I would like the algorithm to classify. Please note I chose to use the superclasses of the objects as opposed to the individual classes in order to limit the number of classes the algorithm would need to decipher between. If this model were to be used in practice, this would not be the realistic case and the individual classes of the objects would need to be utilized.

Because CIFAR-100 consists of tiny 32x32 pixel thumbnail images, this particular object classification model will focus on detecting and classifying these object from a distance. Thus, this would allow autonomous driving vehicles to detect and classify images from a long way away, while objects captured on the car's cameras may still be small, and give the car adequate time to make a decision reagarding the object.

The baseline this algorithm would need to beat is difficult to pinpoint. For this lab I am going to argue that in order for this algorithm to be deployable it needs to be 100% accurate in classifing these objects as there is really no room for error in the case of self driving cars. In practice this algorithm would be trained and deployed in autonomous driving vehicles to provide the vehicle with real time prediction regarding the objects in its surroundings.

Possible third party users would be companies such as Tesla, Uber, Apple, Google, and Waymo, to name a few, who are all currently competing to develop self driving vehicles.

2.4 Min Max Scaling the Data¶

Before passing the data to the convolutional neural network, the pixel values need to be scaled as to not saturate the neurons and allow the network to properly train. To bring the pixel values onto the same scale there are two approaches one could take: normalization (Min-Max Scaling) or standardization (Standard Scaling). Because I am working with image data, I will use Min Max Scaling to bring the pixels across all images onto the same scale, between 0 and 1. This is because, when working with images the data should be normalized and not standardized. Mathematically the normalization I will perform on the images is shown below:

$$ xnorm^{i} = \frac{x^{i} - xmin} {xmax - xmin} $$

where x superscript i is a particular pixel values and xmin and xmax are the maximum and minimum values pixel values in the image.

Below, I show the effect that of both normalization and standardization has on the images. It is clear from the images below that normalization yields better image quality than standardization.

3. Evaluation Metric¶

In choosing an appropriate evaluation metric in which to evaluate this algorithms performance, we must understand how this algorithm would be used in a deployed model. Lets consider an example to bring to light the appropriate evaluation metric for this model.

Consider Uber has placed our deployed model in their new taxis. Their reason for using our model is two fold. One, they want their cars to drive safely and be able to detect and avoid collisions with object cars are likely to encounter while driving, and two, they want to identify people who are waiting for thier uber cabs so they can pick up their customers.

Looking at fold one above, the clear evaluation metric is recall. That is, we would want our algorithm to avoid false negatives, for example in order to avoid the case of our algorithm predicting a person is not a person, or a bicycle is not a bicycle, and coming into collision with either of the two. In considering the case where a false negative is predicted by the algorithm, this would be catastrophic for a self driving vehicle, and could result in fatal consequences for pedestrians in the vicinity of the vehicle, or for the passengers in the car.

In considering fold two above, the clear evaluation metric is precision. That is, we want our algorithm to avoid predicting false positives. For example, predicting a sidewalk advertisement containing a picture of a person is actually a person waiting for their cab. In examining the case of predicting false positives more closely, the car would not operate very efficiently if it was stopping to pick up customers who it believed were people but were actually just pictures of people. With this it came to my attention that the CIFAR-100 dataset may not be the most realistic image data to train an autonomous driving vehicle classification model on since it is simply pictures of things. For instance, by using the CIFAR-100 images to train the CNN to classify people, if it saw an advertisement with a picture of a person on it, this would probably look similar to the images used to train the model, thus the model would not be wrong in predicting a picture of a person is an actual person because that is EXACTLY how it was trained. However, keep this in mind and lets put this aside for now.

From the above it is seen that a combination of both precision and recall are important to the fluid and cohesive operation of a self driving Uber, as in the example. As a result of this, the appropriate evaluation metric in which to evaluate this algorithms performance is the F1-Measure, which is defined mathematically as below:

$$ F1-Measure\hspace{1mm}(F) = \frac{2\hspace{0.2mm}r\hspace{0.2mm}p} {r\hspace{0.2mm}p}$$

where, recall (r) and precision (p) are defined as:

$$ Precision\hspace{1mm}(p) = \frac{True\hspace{1mm} Positives} {True\hspace{1mm} Positives\hspace{1mm} + \hspace{1mm}False\hspace{1mm}Positives}$$$$ Recall\hspace{1mm}(r) = \frac{True\hspace{1mm} Positives} {True\hspace{1mm} Positives\hspace{1mm} + \hspace{1mm}False\hspace{1mm}Negatives}$$

With the F1-Measure, there are a few averaging options in which to choose from to better tailor the F1-Measure for this dataset and classification task. In choosing whether to 'micro', 'macro', or 'weighted' average the F1-Measure, we must consider the class distribution of the dataset. Lets do so below:

From the figure above, it is seen that the class distribution in the dataset is equal at 25 percent across all classes. Thus, we do not need to account for any class imbalance averaging in the F1-Measure. However, because we are performing multi-classification, we need a way to combine our F1-Measure for multiple classes, using either a micro or macro average. Because there is an equal number of instances in each class, I chose to use a micro averaged F1-Measure, which weights all instances equally.

To summarize, the appropriate evaluation metric in which to measure this algorithms performance is a micro averaged F1-Measure, defined mathematically as:

$$ F1\hspace{1mm} macro = \frac{2\hspace{0.2mm}(TP_0 +...+ TP_3)} {2 \hspace{0.2mm}(TP_0+...+TP_3) + \hspace{1mm}FP_0 +...FP_3} $$

4. Method for Dividing Data into Training and Test Splits¶

In choosing the appropriate method in which to divide the data for this classification task into training and testing splits, we must consider the the amount of data we have to work with, and how this algorithm will be used in a deployed model.

In addressing the amount of data I have to work with, the original CIFAR-100 dataset consists of 60,000 images, which is a large amount of data. However, because I chose a subset of the CIFAR-100 dataset for application in the autonomous driving industry, the dataset I am left with is comprised of 12,000 images. While this is still a good amount of data, in training convolutional neural networks, it is helpful to have lots of data to train these algorithms for good generalization performance. Thus, in order to make efficient use of the 12,000 images in my dataset, I chose to use Stratified 10-fold cross validation. K-fold cross validation efficiently uses small amounts of data to train and test algorithms by training the algorithm on K-1 folds and testing the algorithm on the remaining fold. Thus, even though I am limited to 12,000 images, using 10-Fold cross validation ensures the algorithm will be trained and testing over vast amounts of data.

This cross validation technique accurately represents how this algorithm would be used in practice for the following reasons: In a deployed model, for this algorithm to even be considered deployable, as discussed in the business case, it would need to achieve 100% classification accuracy all the time. Because K-Fold cross validation trains and tests the algorithm across a vast amount of data, it gives an accurate measure for the generalization performance of an algorithm. Thus, we can see how the algorithm performs across varying instances as it would be subjected to in a deployed model. Therefore, I believe stratified K-Fold cross validation most accurately reflects how this algorithm would be used when deployed in a self driving car.

However, because performing 10-fold cross validation would take hours to run when training some of the CNNs below, for the sake of time and getting this lab done, I will use 2 fold cross validation, which should still give us a descent gauge of the generalization performance of the models. Also, it should be noted that using data expansion below, I actually doubled the size of my training data, which makes 2 fold cross validation even more appropriate in the context due to the large amount of training data.

5. Data Augmentation and Expansion¶

As discussed in business case, this dataset is composed of images of people, trees, large man-made outdoor things, and vehicles, inherited from the CIFAR-100 dataset. The convolutional neural networks in this assignment aim to classify these objects for use in autonomous driving vehicles to enable them to better understand their surroundings.

The CIFAR-100 is somewhat unrealistic training data to use for the training a classification algorithm for a self driving vehicle. It consists of cenetered images, containing the whole object, with appropriate orientations, which really does not accurately reflect what a camera on a self driving car would see while driving. However, we do not have to be completely limited by the images we are given. Using data augmentation techniques, we can alter the images from the CIFAR-100 dataset to more accurately represent images a self driving car's camera would capture.

For instance, when a car is driving it may capture a bicycle traveling from right to left or left to right according to its perspective. This goes for all vehicles a car may encounter on the road such as trucks, motorcycles, ect... Thus, it would make sense to flip some images around the y-axis (horizontally) to depict the various directions cars, bikes, and motorcycles could be traveling.

Also, the cameras in autonomous driving vehicles may not always capture the full object in one single frame. Meaning sometimes the camera may only detect half a bicycle or car. To depict this in the original images, it would be sensible to shift the location of the image in the frame, either up or down in the frame, or left and right, or perhaps both.

Another scenario that should be accounted for is the distance these objects are from the car at the time they are caught on the cars camera. To account for this, the zoom of the images should be altered to reflect objects that are in a close proximity to the car and objects that are very far away from the car at the time they are detected by the cars camera.

A way to account for these occurrences is, as mentioned above, to use image augmentation and data expansion. Using the built-in keras ImageDataGenerator I will create a new set of augmented images, reflecting the scenarios discussed above. Doing so, I will double the size of my image data (data expansion) by creating 10,000 new augmented images, according to the augmentations above, and append them to the original images.

In the ImageDataGenerator below, I will set the following parameters to represent the image augmentations discussed above:

1) rotation_range to 5: to represent object that have imperfect orientations in the cars camera

2) width and height shift range to 0.1: to represent objects that may have not been fully caught in the cars camera

3) zoom_range to 0.5: to represent objects that may be in very close or very far proximity to the car

4) horizontal_flip to True: to represent objects that are traveling from right to left or left to right across the camera perspective.

5) cval to 0.1: to better fill the pixel values outside the boundaries in appropriate cases

6.1 Architecture 1: Class Example (cnn0)¶

To begin, lets start with a fairly simple CNN. The following CNN is an architecture we looked at in class to classify the fashion MNIST dataset. It consists of 2 convolutional layers and two max pooling layers, generated by the for loop in the code below. Following the convolutional and max pooling layers are a flattening layer and two dense layers. A detailed description of the layer structure for this architecture can be found in the cnn0.summary() below.

def create_cnn0():
    cnn0 = Sequential()

    num_filt_layers = [24, 48]
    for num_filters in num_filt_layers:
        cnn0.add(Conv2D(filters = num_filters,
                        input_shape = (32,32,3), # Channels last!!!
                        kernel_size = (3,3), 
                        padding = 'same'))
        cnn0.add(Activation('relu'))
        cnn0.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last'))

    cnn0.add(Flatten())
    cnn0.add(Dense(100))
    cnn0.add(Activation('relu'))
    cnn0.add(Dense(n_classes))
    cnn0.add(Activation('softmax'))
    
    return cnn0

6.2 Architecture 2: Alex Net Style Architecture (cnn1)¶

The next architecture I will explore has an AlexNet style convolutional phase with some dropout in the final layers. The main architectural difference in this architecture is the dropout in the final layers. Dropout is a regularization technique used to reduce over-fitting in the CNN. Using dropout, only a subset of the neurons in the network will be trained over each epoch. Thus, not every weight in the model will be updated for each epoch. With dropout I would expect to see a better f1 score using this architecture.

In [ ]:
def create_cnn1():
    cnn1 = Sequential()
    cnn1.add(Conv2D(filters = 32,
                  input_shape = (32,32,3),
                  kernel_size = (3,3),
                  padding = 'same',
                  activation = 'relu'))

    cnn1.add(Conv2D(filters = 64,
                   kernel_size = (3,3),
                   padding = 'same',
                   activation = 'relu'))

    cnn1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last'))

    cnn1.add(Dropout(0.25))
    cnn1.add(Flatten())
    cnn1.add(Dense(64, activation = 'relu'))
    cnn1.add(Dropout(0.5))
    cnn1.add(Dense(n_classes, activation = 'softmax'))
    
    return cnn1

6.3 Architecture 3: LeNet Style Architecture with Resnet Style Blocks (cnn2)¶

The architecture below is substantially deeper and more complex than the architectures examined above. Based on the LeNet architecture, this CNN introduces three new techniques: weight initialization, L2 regularization, and ResNet style bypass blocks. By appropriately initializing the weights of the CNN, we can help the network learn. Regularization is another technique that is used to avoid model over-fitting. By incorporating bypass layers, the problem of vanishing gradients is basically eliminated. This is because now when performing back propagation, the network can go around or 'bypass', each layer as well as go through them and update the weights in the layers behind. Thus, this ensures gradients in the early layers of the network will remain large enough to meaningfully update the weights in the layers. A illustration of a ResNet style bypass block is shown below.

Lets see what this network can do!

The ResNet-Style Bypass is described in the following:

def create_cnn2():
    
    l2_lambda = 0.0001
    
    input_holder = Input(shape = (32,32,3))
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 32,
               input_shape  = (32,32,3),
               kernel_size = (3,3),
               kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(input_holder)
    
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 32,
               kernel_size = (3,3),
               kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x_split = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 64,
               kernel_size = (1,1),
               kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x_split)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 64,
               kernel_size = (3,3),
               kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 32,
               kernel_size = (1,1),
               kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Add()([x, x_split])
    x = Activation('relu')(x)
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    x = Dropout(0.25)(x)
    x = Dense(256)(x)
    x = Activation('relu')(x)
    x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
    x = Dense(n_classes)(x)
    x = Activation('softmax')(x)
    
    cnn2 = Model(inputs = input_holder, outputs = x)
    
    return cnn2

6.3.1 CNN2 Modified (cnn2_mod)¶
In [ ]:
def create_cnn2_mod():
    
    l2_lambda = 0.0001
    
    input_holder = Input(shape = (32,32,3))
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 32,
               input_shape  = (32,32,3),
               kernel_size = (9,9),
               kernel_initializer = 'lecun_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(input_holder)
    
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 64,
               kernel_size = (6,6),
               kernel_initializer = 'lecun_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x_split = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 32,
               kernel_size = (6,6),
               kernel_initializer = 'lecun_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x_split)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 128,
               kernel_size = (3,3),
               kernel_initializer = 'lecun_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Conv2D(filters = 64,
               kernel_size = (1,1),
               kernel_initializer = 'lecun_uniform',
               kernel_regularizer = l2(l2_lambda),
               padding = 'same',
               activation = 'relu',
               data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    
    x = Add()([x, x_split])
    x = Activation('relu')(x)
    x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last')(x)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    x = Dropout(0.1)(x)
    x = Dense(256)(x)
    x = Activation('relu')(x)
    x = Dropout(0.25)(x)
    x = Dense(n_classes)(x)
    x = Activation('softmax')(x)
    
    cnn2_mod = Model(inputs = input_holder, outputs = x)
    
    return cnn2_mod

In comparing the performance of the different CNN architectures in regards to the f1 score of the CNN, lets look at both the mean f1 score over the two fold cross validation, and the standard deviations in the f1 score. Viewing the plot on the left, it is seen that cnn0_mod, cnn1, and cnn1_mod, achieved the highest mean f1 score, with a mean f1 score of roughly ~ 76%. While we could say, that cnn0_mod is the best performer, due to the fact it achieved the highest mean f1 score, this assumption would be short-sided, not taking into account valuable information such as the standard deviation of the f1 score for the CNN. To decipher which is the best performing CNN, between the three top performing CNN architectures, lets examine the standard deviations in the f1 scores for the different architectures. In viewing the graph on the right, we can see that cnn0_mod, which has the highest mean f1 score, also had the highest standard deviation by far, eliminating this CNN architecture from the three top contenders. cnn1 and cnn1_mod (the Alex net style convolutional phase CNNs) had roughly the same mean f1 score over the two folds, however the cnn1_mod architecture has a significantly lesser standard deviation in its f1 score. Thus from viewing the mean f1 score of the CNN in conjunction with the standard deviation, it is apparent that cnn1_mod is the best performing model.

However, from solely observing the mean f1 score and standard deviation, how sure of myself can I be when I say that cnn1_mod is the best performing CNN architecture. To find out I will perform a statistical T-Test to determine if I can say with 95% certainty that cnn1_mod is better than cnn1.

6.5 Statistical Comparision of cnn1 and cnn1_mod¶

Above, we established that cnn1_mod was the best performing CNN architecture by using the mean f1 score and standard deviation in the f1 scores over the two fold cross validation the CNN was tested upon. Via the same method, cnn1 came in second place as the next best performing CNN architecture. In this section, lets test if we can say with 95% certainty that cnn1_mod is the better model.

To statistically compare the performance of the two CNN architectures, I am going to perform a T-Test. More specifically, I will approximate the bounds using the folds of the cross fold validation to get a mean and variance of the f1 scores for the CNNs. I believe this is the most appropriate means of generating confidence intervals because both models were trained using the same data. For the T-Test, I will use a t value of 2.26 and k = 10 (note that this is lowercase k and not capital K, which indicated the number of folds in the cross validation).

If the resulting confidence interval between the two CNNs does not include 0, then statistically, with 95% confidence, we can say that the cnn1_mod CNN architecture is the better CNN.

In [50]:
f1_score_cnn1_mod_ttest = np.array(f1_score_cnn1_mod)
f1_score_cnn1_ttest = np.array(f1_score_cnn1)

k = 10
t = 2.26 / np.sqrt(k)

e = (1 - f1_score_cnn1_mod_ttest) - (1 - f1_score_cnn1_ttest)
stdtot = np.std(e)
dbar = np.mean(e)
print(f'Confidence Interval: {dbar - t * stdtot} --> {dbar + t * stdtot}')

Confidence Interval: 0.007512223818650329 --> 0.015087776181349735

In statistically comparing the CNNs above, I can say with 95% confidence that cnn1_mod in the better CNN architecture due to the fact that the confidence interval does not include 0. Thus, cnn1_mod is the best performing CNN architecture of the above CNNs.

def create_cnn_best():
    cnn1_mod = Sequential()
    cnn1_mod.add(Conv2D(filters = 32,
                  input_shape = (32,32,3),
                  kernel_size = (6,6),
                  padding = 'same',

                   kernel_size = (3,3),

    cnn1_mod.add(Dropout(0.5))
    cnn1_mod.add(Dense(n_classes, activation = 'softmax'))

6.7.1 Reciever Operating Characteristic and Area Under the Curve¶

Below, we are going to look at the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve and the Area Under the Curve (AUC) as one method to compare a Standard MLP to my best CNN. ROC curves are useful tools which to aid in selecting classification models based on their performance with respect to the False Positive Rate and True Positive Rate. ROC curves are constructed by shifting the decision threshold of the classifier, and counting the number of True Positives and False Positives both above and below the threshold. The diagonal of an ROC curve represents random guessing, while a perfect classifier would have a True Positive Rate of 1 and a False Positive Rate if 0, represented in the ROC curve below. Once an ROC curve has been calculated, more information can be derived from the AUC to characterize the classification performance of a model, with a greater AUC commonly indicating a better model[3].

Below, lets compute and graphically examine the ROC and AUC of a Standard MLP and my best CNN.

[3] Raschka, Sebastian & Mirkalili, Vahid. Python Machine Learning.

    X_test_cnn = X_train_aug[test]
    y_train_cnn = to_categorical(y_train_aug[train], n_classes)
    y_test_cnn = to_categorical(y_train_aug[test], n_classes)
    
    X_test_smlp = X_train_mlp[test]
    
    
    pred_cnn = cnn_best.predict(X_test_cnn)
    
    pred_mlp = mlp.predict(X_test_smlp)
    
    # CNN
    perclass_mean_tpr = 0.0
    roc_auc = 0
    classes = np.unique(y_train_aug)
    
    for j in classes:
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train_aug[test], 
                                         pred_cnn[:,j], 
                                         pos_label = j)
        perclass_mean_tpr += interp(mean_fpr, fpr, tpr)
        perclass_mean_tpr[0] = 0.0
        roc_auc += auc(fpr,tpr)
        
    perclass_mean_tpr /= len(classes)
    roc_auc /= len(classes)
    mean_tpr += perclass_mean_tpr
    
    plt.plot(mean_fpr, perclass_mean_tpr, '--', lw = 1, label = 'CNN Mean Class ROC fold %d area = %0.2f' % (i + 1, roc_auc))
    
    # MLP
    perclass_mean_tpr = 0.0
    roc_auc = 0
    classes = np.unique(y_train_aug)
    
    for j in classes:
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train_aug[test], 
                                         pred_mlp[:,j], 
                                         pos_label = j)
        perclass_mean_tpr += interp(mean_fpr, fpr, tpr)
        perclass_mean_tpr[0] = 0.0
        roc_auc += auc(fpr,tpr)
        
    perclass_mean_tpr /= len(classes)
    roc_auc /= len(classes)
    mean_tpr += perclass_mean_tpr
    
    plt.plot(mean_fpr, perclass_mean_tpr, '--', lw = 1, label = 'MLP Mean Class ROC fold %d area = %0.2f' % (i + 1, roc_auc))

# The following code is taken and slightly modified from Raschka, Sebastian & Mirkalili, Vahid. Python Machine Learning.
plt.plot([0,1], [0,1], linestyle = ':', color = 'black', label = 'Random Guessing')
    
plt.plot([0,0,1], [0,1,1], linestyle = '-', color = 'black', label = 'Perfect Classifier' )

plt.grid()
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate', fontsize = 10)
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate', fontsize = 10)
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend(loc = 'best', fontsize = 10)
plt.show()

Using the ROC curve and AUC, lets come to a determination of which classifier is the better choice for the classification task at hand. Please note the perfect classifier and random guessing curves plotted in the graph above.

In examining the ROC curve, it can be determined that the my best CNN is the better classifier compared to the Standard MLP. This is apparent by the CNN ROC curves being closer to that of a perfect classifier over both folds. Also, the average AUC over the two folds for the my best CNN was 0.895, while the average AUC over the two folds for the Standard MLP was 0.835.

Since there is no overlap between any of the curves, there is not really any further considerations necessary from the ROC curve and AUC in comparing the performance of the two classifiers, since my best CNN has obvious better classification performance in terms of it's ROC curves and average AUC.

6.7.2 Statistical Comparision¶

Lets again, determine how certain we can be when we say that my best CNN is the better classifier compared to the Standard MLP. To determine if we can say with 95% certainty that my best CNN is the better classifier, let again perform the same T-Test we performed in section 6.5.

However, in this T-Test I am going to compare the models over both cross validation folds.

7. Transfer Learning¶

In the following section, I am going to explore a transfer learning technique to pre-train the weights in the convolutinal layers of the CNN created below. Using this technique, we can use the weights of pre-trained verifiable convolutional neural networks, such as VGG16, ResNet, or Xception, to name a few, to initialize the weights in the initial convolutional layers of CNNs we want to create, thus only having to train the weights in the dense layers.

For this particular example, I am going to use the 'imagenet' weights from ResNet50 to initialize the weights of the convolutional layers in the CNN I create below. Then I will take the output of the pre-trained convolutional layers from ResNet50 and place them through two dense layers.

7.1 Comparison of Transfer Learning to Training from Scratch¶

This is sort of an unfair comparison at the moment because the CNN trained from scratch (my best CNN) was able to train for 50 epochs, while the CNN used in the transfer learning model was only able to train for 1 epoch. But, what if we wanted to get a fair assessment of how these two models actually compare. Lets level the playing field a bit. Since I do not have the resources to train the transfer learning model for 50 epochs, lets instead only train the CNN in my best CNN for 1 epoch and over the same 10,000 instances and see how the models compare.

It should also be noted that the transfer learning CNN was trained on 224 x 224 x 3 images because this is the size of images ResNet50 was trained on as well, so lets also reflect this is the CNN trained from scratch.

In [105]:
def create_cnn_scratch():
    cnn_scratch = Sequential()
    cnn_scratch.add(Conv2D(filters = 32,
                  input_shape = (224,224,3),
                  kernel_size = (6,6),
                  padding = 'same',
                  activation = 'relu'))

    cnn_scratch.add(Conv2D(filters = 64,
                   kernel_size = (3,3),
                   padding = 'same',
                   activation = 'relu'))

    cnn_scratch.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), data_format = 'channels_last'))

    cnn_scratch.add(Dropout(0.4))
    cnn_scratch.add(Flatten())
    cnn_scratch.add(Dense(64, activation = 'relu'))
    cnn_scratch.add(Dropout(0.5))
    cnn_scratch.add(Dense(n_classes, activation = 'softmax'))
    
    return cnn_scratch

In [132]:
def compare_scratch_transer(cnn, trans, X_test, y_test):
    plt.figure(figsize =(20,5))
    if cnn is not None:
        yhat = np.argmax(cnn.predict(X_test), axis = 1)
        f1 = f1_score(y_test, yhat, average = 'micro')
        plt.subplot(1,2,1)
        cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm, axis = 1)[:, np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', cmap = 'Blues')
        plt.title(f'CNN from Scratch : F1 Score {f1}')
    
    if trans is not None:
        yhat = np.argmax(trans.predict(X_test), axis = 1)
        f1 = f1_score(y_test, yhat, average = 'micro')
        plt.subplot(1,2,2)
        cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm, axis = 1)[:, np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', cmap = 'Blues')
        plt.title(f'Transfer Learning : F1 Score {f1}')

We can see now that the cnn from scratch and the transfer learning model have been trained over the same exact upscaled images and for the same number of epochs. From this, the transfer learning model seems to be the better classifier in terms of classification performance and f1 measure. Off the bat with one epoch of training, the transfer learning model was able achieve a classification accuracy of 62% in class 0 and 47% in class 2, thats not horrible! On the contrary, the cnn from scratch after one training iteration basically classified all images ass class 2, which really means it is guessing all images belong to the same class.

Let's really examine the classification performance of these two models by taking a look at the ROC curve and AUC for the both models.

I thought it would be an interesting comparison to look at the training time per epoch and f1 score these two models were able to achieve after the one epoch. From this, it is apparent that the transfer learning model seems like it has the potential to be the better classifier once again. It took only about 35 minutes per epoch to train, 17 minutes less than it took to train the CNN from scratch for the same 1 epoch. Also, with only 1 epoch the transfer learning model was actually able to start classifying some images, and had an f1 score of 32%, while the CNN from scratch had an f1 score of 25 % after 1 epoch and really just classified everything as class 2.

8. Closing Thoughts¶

The purpose of this lab was to create a CNN that could be deployed and used in autonomous driving vehicles to help them classify objects in their surroundings. The dataset I used to train and test the CNNs created above was the CIFAR-100 dataset, which looking back is really an innapropraite dataset to use in this scenario. It consists on tiny thumbnail images which are not quite realistic in what a car would actually see while driving around. While, I was able to argue a case for why it could be plausable, it really is not ideal data to use. I believe more appropraite data to use to train classifiers of self driving cars would be still frames video content captured on the cameras of self driving cars, with corresponding labels for objects in the frames.

Due to the misuse of this data for this classification task, I would never deploy this model for use in a self driving car. Also, I really believe for use in a self driving car these models should achieve a much higher generalization performance than the model in this assigment were able to achieve.
